ID  - 36143130
T1  - The Impact of Non-Invasive Ventilation on Sleep Quality in COPD Patients.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.3390/jcm11185483
A1  - Wollsching-Strobel, Maximilian
A1  - Bauer, Iris Anna
A1  - Baur, Johannes Julian
A1  - Majorski, Daniel Sebastian
A1  - Magnet, Friederike Sophie
A1  - Storre, Jan Hendrik
A1  - Windisch, Wolfram
A1  - Schwarz, Sarah Bettina
Y1  - 2022//
Y2  - 20220919//
N2  - BACKGROUND: Non-invasive ventilation (NIV) has been shown to be the most appropriate therapy for COPD patients with chronic respiratory failure. While physiological parameters and long-term outcome frequently serve as primary outcomes, very few studies have primarily addressed the impact of NIV initiation on sleep quality in COPD., METHODS: This single-center prospective cohort study comprised NIV-naive patients with COPD. All patients underwent polysomnographic evaluation both at baseline and at 3 months follow-up, accompanied by the assessment of health-related quality of life (HRQL) using the Severe Respiratory Insufficiency Questionnaire (SRI) and the Epworth Sleepiness Scale (ESS). A subgroup evaluation was performed to address the impact of comorbid obstructive sleep apnea syndrome (OSAS)., RESULTS: Forty-six patients were enrolled and twenty-five patients completed the follow-up period (66.7 +/- 7.4 years). NIV resulted in an increase in slow-wave sleep (+2% (-3.5/7.5), p = 0.465) and rapid eye movement sleep (+2.2% (-1.0/5.4), p = 0.174), although no statistical significance could be detected. ESS (-1.7(-3.6/0.1), p = 0.066) also showed a positive trend. Significant improvements in the Respiratory Disturbance Index (RDI) (-12.6(-23.7/-1.5), p = 0.027), lung function parameters, transcutaneous PCO2 and the SRI summary scale (4.5(0.9/8), p = 0.016) were observed., CONCLUSION: NIV therapy does not decrease sleep quality and is even capable of improving HRQL, transcutaneous PaCO2, daytime sleepiness and RDI, and the latter especially holds true for patients with comorbid OSAS.
